# Security Review: `app.js`

I reviewed the file thoroughly. It's a small (~22 line) Express app with two endpoints (`/health`, `/users`) and no input handling, database, auth, or file I/O. Most OWASP Top 10 categories (injection, IDOR, SSRF, deserialization, XXE) simply don't apply because there's no user input being processed.

That said, here are legitimate findings and hardening recommendations:

## Findings

### 1. Missing security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
No `helmet` middleware — responses lack `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP, etc.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No rate limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)
Both endpoints are unauthenticated and unthrottled — trivially DoS-able.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 3. PII exposure on `/users` (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control / A02)
`/users` returns email addresses with no authentication or authorization. Even if the data is seed data today, the shape invites real PII later.

```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  // verify JWT / session
  if (!req.user) return res.status(401).end();
  next();
}
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

Also strip sensitive fields when serializing:
```js
res.json(users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })));
```

### 4. No CORS policy defined (A05)
Default Express behavior may or may not be what you want. Be explicit:
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: 'https://your-frontend.example', methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 5. Hardcoded port, no HTTPS, no host binding (A05)
`app.listen(3000)` binds to all interfaces. Use env config and terminate TLS at a proxy or with `https.createServer`:
```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, '127.0.0.1', () => { /* ... */ });
```

### 6. No error handler / stack-trace leakage (A05, A09)
Add a final error handler so uncaught errors don't leak internals, and add request logging:
```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined'));

app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});
```

### 7. No body size / payload limits (A04)
Not currently parsing bodies, but add defensive defaults before you do:
